{
  "version": "storylock-story-draft-v1",
  "templateId": "emperor-new-clothes-en",
  "language": "en-US",
  "storyTitle": "The Emperor's New Clothes",
  "summary": "Emperor Lorenzo is deceived by Marco and Pietro, two swindlers who promise magical cloth visible only to the wise. His vanity carries him into a public parade, where a child speaks plainly and exposes the lie.",
  "storyPlot": "In 1710, in the early 18th century, a summer morning opened as a bright day over Fantasia, the proud capital of the emperor's realm. In the palace, gardens in bloom surrounded halls of palace splendor. Lorenzo, the Ruler and monarch of Fantasia, loved New clothes and splendid attire more than court reports, and he felt excited and proud whenever tailors praised his taste.\n\nInto this sunny, bright morning came Marco and Pietro, two swindlers. They were Swindlers and tricksters who knew how to flatter emperor's vanity. They offered The promise of invisible cloth, saying it could be seen only by wise and worthy people. Lorenzo's vanity made the offer irresistible, so he ordered gold, silk, and a private workroom prepared for them at once.\n\nLorenzo sent Alberto (old minister), a Minister and trusted advisor, to inspect the work. Alberto saw only empty looms, yet fear made him praise the cloth. Later Bruno (young officer), an officer and official, performed another inspection and also lied. More Inspections followed, more lying spread through the palace, and preparation for a public parade continued as if the invisible robe were real.\n\nDuring the parade later that day, the sunny weather turned warm over the city streets. Lorenzo walked among the crowd beneath colorful banners while cheering crowds filled both sides of the road. Then came The child shouting the truth: the child said the emperor had no clothes. At first there was only a crowd's whisper, but the whisper grew until Lorenzo felt The emperor realizing he was naked, and shame struck him in front of everyone.\n\nLater that evening, after the parade, Lorenzo returned from the city streets to The palace and shut himself inside the emperor's chamber. He felt Foolish, humiliated, and ashamed. The lesson stayed with him: Vanity is foolish, and children speak truth when frightened adults and flattering officials will not.",
